39:24.762 --> 39:30.168
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to one
woman's efforts to find answers
in one of the world's most

39:30.168 --> 39:32.604
distressed school systems.

39:32.604 --> 39:36.674
Special correspondent Fred de
Sam Lazaro reports from Karachi,
Pakistan, part of his series

39:36.674 --> 39:39.310
Agents for Change.

39:39.310 --> 39:44.549
FRED DE SAM LAZARO:
Eleven-year-old Aqsa (ph) has
high ambitions.

39:44.549 --> 39:50.121
GIRL: First, I want to be a
public speaker, and then
president of Pakistan to change.

39:50.121 --> 39:55.860
FRED DE SAM LAZARO:
To change things?

39:55.860 --> 40:00.431
How do you harness the energy
and the enthusiasm of young
children?

40:00.431 --> 40:02.867
If you became president of
Pakistan, what would you like to
do?

40:02.867 --> 40:07.171
GIRL: First, I will clean the
litter, because the biggest
problem is litter.

40:07.171 --> 40:10.875
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: In Lyari,
one of Karachi's toughest
neighborhoods, Aqsa is part of
an

40:10.875 --> 40:15.046
experiment started six years ago
called the Kiran (ph) School.
The children here are

40:15.046 --> 40:19.417
encouraged to think big, to use
their imaginations. But the
gritty reality just outside of a

40:19.417 --> 40:22.587
city often racked by terrorism
and violence looms large.

40:22.587 --> 40:27.191
GIRL: There are many people who
are like, they are heartless, so
they kill people.

40:27.191 --> 40:31.796
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: What kind
of terrorism do you see in
Lyari?

40:31.796 --> 40:35.967
GIRL: They killed one man at
night. It was late, 2:00. They
came and they killed

40:35.967 --> 40:37.835
and went.

40:37.835 --> 40:41.372
FRED DE SAM LAZARO:
Eleven-year-old Hammad (ph) also
has witnessed killing first
hand.

40:41.372 --> 40:45.677
He wants to be a robotics
scientist when he grows up.

40:45.677 --> 40:49.747
BOY: Robots, like, do
everything. And they will stop
terrorism, not kill them, but

40:49.747 --> 40:53.451
they will stop terrorism and
just give to the police.

40:53.451 --> 40:56.321
SABINA KHATRI, Founder, Kiran
School: He said that, why can't
we have robots in Lyari

40:56.321 --> 40:57.989
as policemen?

40:57.989 --> 41:01.726
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Sabina
Khatri is the school founder.

41:01.726 --> 41:05.863
SABINA KHATRI: Nobody can kill
the robots. The bad people will
be defeated.

41:05.863 --> 41:11.936
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: A mother of
grown children, Khatri lived in
Europe for many years before

41:11.936 --> 41:16.507
returning to Karachi. She
started the Kiran School six
years ago, based on the
Montessori

41:16.507 --> 41:22.447
learning model, admitting just
20 students each year, the goal,
prepare them to attend

41:22.447 --> 41:25.650
top private English-language
schools, alongside children from
Karachi's tiny upper class.

41:25.650 --> 41:29.354
She's raised scholarships and
donations in a foundation for
her social enterprise. The

41:29.354 --> 41:32.090
children have thrived, Khatri
says, even become Harvard
material.

41:32.090 --> 41:37.995
SABINA KHATRI: And this is one
of the principals who told me
that this kid can make it to
Harvard.

41:37.995 --> 41:42.934
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Problem is,
the vast majority of children in
Lyari and Pakistan

41:42.934 --> 41:49.240
will go nowhere. Just 2 percent
of the government's budget goes
to education, and much of that

41:49.240 --> 41:53.644
is squandered. Public schools
are in decrepit condition.
Fifty percent lack electricity;

41:53.644 --> 41:58.916
40 percent have no toilets.
Many are stripped of furniture.
And it gets worse.

41:58.916 --> 42:03.955
It's not uncommon in this
country for there to be public
schools that exist only on
paper.

42:03.955 --> 42:07.992
The money's been allocated, but
no building's been built, no
students enrolled. The only

42:07.992 --> 42:12.997
thing that is up and running is
the payroll for so-called
teachers. They are, in fact,

42:12.997 --> 42:14.866
mostly beneficiaries
of political favors.

42:14.866 --> 42:17.735
Khatri says the
government is starting to

42:17.735 --> 42:22.573
face facts, and it's invited
outsiders to take over failing
schools. A few months

42:22.573 --> 42:28.246
ago, Khatri adopted this Lyari
middle school. Her first task
was to hire new teachers

42:28.246 --> 42:33.551
and tell most of the old ones,
tenured, so they could not be
fired, to just stay away.

42:33.551 --> 42:36.754
SABINA KHATRI: They come and
make -- create troubles in the
school.

42:36.754 --> 42:41.392
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: So, you
would just as soon have them
be...

42:41.392 --> 42:44.695
SABINA KHATRI: Yes. I just
tell them that, if you're
creating trouble here, it's
better

42:44.695 --> 42:48.232
that you don't come.

42:48.232 --> 42:52.336
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Her next
step, rearrange classes to
cluster students by ability, not

42:52.336 --> 42:54.672
grade level.

42:54.672 --> 43:01.946
SABINA KHATRI: Although they do
say that they are in the eighth
grade or ninth grade,

43:01.946 --> 43:06.217
they can't even -- they don't
even know how to write their
name in Urdu, let alone in

43:06.217 --> 43:08.052
English.

43:08.052 --> 43:14.826
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: The
students here have been put in
an intense remedial curriculum.

43:14.826 --> 43:20.565
There's strong emphasis on
inquiry and critical thinking,
instead of the more common rote

43:20.565 --> 43:32.477
learning. The school also
teaches Islamic values that
Khatri says are too often
neglected,

43:32.477 --> 43:38.049
like tolerance. It's a
challenge in a conservative and
in many ways isolated society.

43:38.049 --> 43:43.721
SABINA KHATRI: The biggest
criticism and concern was that
maybe we were very modern,

43:43.721 --> 43:51.629
that they feel that we teach our
children music and dance and we
are making them broad-minded.

43:51.629 --> 43:59.170
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: And she's
poised to take a controversial
step.

43:59.170 --> 44:05.643
SABINA KHATRI: We have actually
taken permission for a
co-education school. So, we
want to

44:05.643 --> 44:09.747
admit girls now, because we
already have 250 boys in school.

44:09.747 --> 44:16.120
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Regular
meetings with parents and the
community are also part of

44:16.120 --> 44:23.027
the job. When one woman at a
recent open house worried the
school was teaching liberal

44:23.027 --> 44:28.132
values, Khatri asked an
11-year-old from the Kiran
School to respond.

44:28.132 --> 44:32.870
SABINA KHATRI: She actually
said that, you know, we believe
in God. The way we have

44:32.870 --> 44:36.807
learned about God is, God is
love. But that is not the way
other children are taught.

44:36.807 --> 44:39.477
It's always taught that God
will punish you. God loves you.

44:39.477 --> 44:40.912
They were quiet.

44:40.912 --> 44:43.681
FRED DE SAM LAZARO:
And accepting?

44:43.681 --> 45:00.998
SABINA KHATRI: It was a
wonderful -- yes, I think so,
because, then, after that, the

45:00.998 --> 45:09.907
same lady, she said, I
want an admission form.

45:09.907 --> 45:22.687
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: One parent
was assuaged, but Khatri says
intolerance remains a threat.

45:22.687 --> 45:36.500
So, community service projects
are another way to win the
neighborhood over. But in

45:36.500 --> 45:42.873
a country racked by instability,
there is no guarantee.

45:42.873 --> 45:58.522
SABINA KHATRI: Anything can
happen to me any time,
especially in the situation I
am,

45:58.522 --> 46:15.439
and especially the kind of
things that have been happening
in our country, because social
workers have been

46:15.439 --> 46:29.687
targeted lately, in the past two
or three years. Anyone who's
trying to help out people,

46:29.687 --> 46:33.991
they just kill them.

46:33.991 --> 47:18.035
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Still,
Khatri, who was recently joined
by a prominent business leader,

47:18.035 --> 47:53.170
plans to persist with what she
calls a promising prototype to
fix a broken school system.

47:53.170 --> 48:04.648
She and many others say it's
where intolerance and most of
Pakistan's social and economic

48:04.648 --> 48:07.284
problems have their root.

48:07.284 --> 48:14.692
I'm Fred de Sam Lazaro for the
"PBS NewsHour" in Karachi,
Pakistan.

